## NFL Elo Power Rankings 2023
This page shows week-by-week NFL power rankings, based on the
[Elo rating system](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elo_rating_system).  The
Elo rating system is a fair way to judge to relative strength of
competitors, and is therefore an objective way to create NFL power
rankings.

Aside from the current ratings and rankings, the previous game results, and
estimate for the next game, can be toggled visible below.

This is not meant to predict the outcome of games/seasons.  My Elo ranking
implementation picks the winner correctly in about 64% of games.  This is merely
a way to create power rankings without involving human bias and emotion.

<details>
        <summary>Elo rating details:</summary>
        <ul>
                <li>An "average" rating is 1500.</li>
                <li>For every game, the better-performing team takes some number of Elo rating points from
                its opponent.</li>
                <li>Home field advantage, rest days, margin of victory/defeat, and of course both teams' ratings,
                are factored into predictions and rating updates.</li>
                <li>The losing team *can* gain Elo rating points, as long as they perform above expectations.</li>
                <li>The winning team *can* lose Elo rating points if they perform below expectations.</li>
                <li>Elo ratings do not move much from week to week.  This minimizes the overreaction from upsets.</li>
                <li>All team ratings move a little bit toward the average during the offseason.</li>
                <li>Ratings are based on previous seasons' ratings going back to the start of the 2013 season.
                I found that adding historic seasons does not change the current ratings much, so at this time
                there is no plan to include 2012 and older data in the ratings.</li>
                <li>If you see an unequal number of rating points exchanged after games, or an
                offseason parity adjustment of 0, it may be because ratings are actually
                floating-point decimal values and are only rounded for display here.</li>
        </ul>
</details>

*Note: I'll try to update this page every week.  This data is somewhat manually updated, so
please bear with me and check back later if I haven't updated things.*
